actions.comment:
Thank you for reporting this!

This crash is related to #1880 — the `SKPaint.Shader` setter passes the handle directly to native code without coordinating thread safety. When you set `brush.Shader = null` while another thread is still using the same paint (or the underlying native render pipeline still holds a reference), the native unref of the old shader can race with its use and cause a fatal crash.

**Workaround (immediate):** Do not share an `SKPaint` instance across threads. Create a separate `SKPaint` for each thread that needs it:

```csharp
// Instead of sharing one brush, create per-call:
using var brush = new SKPaint { Shader = shader };
DrawPath(brush, path);
// brush disposed here — shader lifetime is safe
```

Alternatively, ensure that `brush.Shader = null` is only called after all rendering operations using that brush have fully completed on all threads.

Note that Skia objects (`SKPaint`, `SKCanvas`, etc.) are **not thread-safe**. Each thread should own its own paint objects.
